g.text: User initiates actions like register, login, and data requests.
Client represents an external service requesting authentication.
SSO is the authentication server managing tokens and user accounts.
Database stores user, client, and session data.
Request: Register Client (appName, secret, tokenTTL, refreshTokenTTL, redirectURL)
Create App (appName, secret, tokenTTL, refreshTokenTTL, redirectURL)
Client saves the App Id for future authentication.
Response: no JWT provided, please register account
No JWT means the user is not authenticated yet.
Request: Register Account (email, password, role, appId)
Response: Account Id + JWT (access) + refresh token
JWT (access and refresh) issued upon successful registration.
User receives new tokens (access + refresh) upon login.
Update session: create new JWT (access) and refresh token
Upon session refresh, new tokens are issued.
Client checks the validity of the JWT to authenticate the user.
User must refresh session if JWT is expired.
Check JWT payload (JWT signature (header + payload hashed with secret) does not match)
If JWT is malformed, user must log in again.
